    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1953-04-20T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1953-04-20T00:00:00-05:00" n="766"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d766">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">690D.93/4–2053</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">Memorandum by the Assistant Secretary of State for Near
                        Eastern, South Asian, and African Affairs</hi> (<persName corresp="#p_BHA1"
                        type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Byroade</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#left">
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">top secret</hi>
                    </seg>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">[<placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>,] <date calendar="gregorian" when="1953-04-20">April 20,
                            1953</date>.</dateline>
                </opener>
                <list type="subject">
                    <head>Subject:</head>
                    <item>Informing the British about <persName corresp="#p_HPG1">Paul
                            Hoffman</persName>’s mission on Kashmir.</item>
                </list>
                <p>
                    <persName corresp="#p_HPG1">Paul Hoffman</persName> has reported that he has had
                    a full and free discussion with <persName corresp="#p_NJ1">Nehru</persName>
                    about Kashmir (New Delhi’s 3873).<note n="1" xml:id="d766fn1">
                        <ref target="#d765">
                            <hi rend="italic">Supra</hi>
                        </ref>.</note> He did not, however, specifically advance partition as a
                    solution. <persName corresp="#p_NJ1">Nehru</persName> has given Mr. <persName
                        corresp="#p_HPG1">Hoffman</persName> permission to advise the Pakistan Prime
                    Minister of his, <persName corresp="#p_NJ1">Nehru</persName>’s, eagerness to
                    effect a settlement through direct negotiation. In this connection <persName
                        corresp="#p_NJ1">Nehru</persName> referred to plans for a meeting with the
                    Pakistan Prime Minister some time later. Mr. <persName corresp="#p_HPG1"
                        >Hoffman</persName> is to report <pb facs="0268" n="1318" xml:id="pg_1318"/>
                    the results of his conversation in Karachi to <persName corresp="#p_NJ1"
                        >Nehru</persName> on Wednesday, April 22, when he returns to New Delhi. You
                    will recall that it was decided not to inform the British of the <persName
                        corresp="#p_HPG1">Hoffman</persName> mission at the outset but that
                    depending on what happened a top British official might be told after Mr.
                        <persName corresp="#p_HPG1">Hoffman</persName> arrived. Since it is likely
                    that word will now filter back to London through the High Commissioners’ offices
                    in New Delhi and Karachi, I think you might consider orally informing
                        <persName>John Selwyn Lloyd</persName>, Minister of State, while you are in
                    Paris attending the <gloss target="#t_NATO1">NATO</gloss> meeting. He will head
                    the British delegation.<note n="2" xml:id="d766fn2">Notation on the source text
                        by <persName corresp="#p_ORL1">Roderic L. O’Connor</persName>, Assistant to
                        the Secretary of State: “As I said—Sec mentioned this to Selwyn Lloyd 24
                        April in general way—got no reaction.”</note>
                </p>
            </div>
